{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648494"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:54:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:54:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18315"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18315"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.76,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78651"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11033"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"10836"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78651"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common bacterial cause of acute haematogenous osteomyelitis in children over three years of age?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gram-negative bacteria","Haemophilus","Staphylococcus","Streptococcus","Pseudomonas"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute haematogenous osteomyelitis is an infection of the bone that occurs when bacteria spread through the bloodstream to the bone. It is a common condition in children, particularly those over three years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common bacterial cause of acute haematogenous osteomyelitis in children over three years of age is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. This organism is responsible for the majority of cases in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram-negative bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E - These are less common causes of osteomyelitis in children\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a less common cause, especially after the introduction of the \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E type b vaccine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - While \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E can cause osteomyelitis, it is less common than \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more commonly associated with osteomyelitis in specific situations, such as puncture wounds, rather than haematogenous spread\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute haematogenous osteomyelitis in children over three years of age is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus.","Streptococcus pyogenes can also cause osteomyelitis in children, but it is less common than Staphylococcus aureus.","Gram-negative bacteria and Pseudomonas are less common causes of osteomyelitis in children."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers","Momodu II, Savaliya V. Osteomyelitis. [Updated 2023 May 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532250/","Folpe, A., \u0026 Nielsen, G. P. (Eds.). (2022). Bone and Soft Tissue Pathology E-Book: A Volume in the Foundations in Diagnostic Pathology Series. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18315"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63994"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T21:12:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T00:17:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11033"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78651"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag